b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe01157.htm)  [Next](sbe01159.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBW6/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 1 (SBE01)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### TWENTY-FOURTH KHA _N_ _D_ A.\n\n1\\. 'Where one sees nothing else, hears nothing else, understands nothing\nelse, that is the Infinite. Where one sees something else, hears something\nelse, understands something else, that is the finite. The Infinite is\nimmortal, the finite is mortal.'\n\n'Sir, in what does the Infinite rest?'\n\n'In its own greatness--or not even in greatness [2](sbe01159.htm#fn_321).'\n\n2\\. 'In the world they call cows and horses, elephants and gold, slaves,\nwives, fields and houses greatness. I do not mean this,' thus he spoke; 'for\nin that case one being (the possessor) rests in something else, (but the\nInfinite cannot rest in something different from itself)\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: VII, 25](sbe01159.htm)\n\n"